{Getting ten of the strongest players in Africa to face each other will
inevitably lead to some of them having a less desirable result. It was the
case of Arthur but the scores are rarely presenting the full story, as he did
have a couple of very well conducted games. But the clock is mercilessly
ticking...} 19. Nxf7 $1 Kxf7 20. Qf3+ Nf6 21. exf6 gxf6 22. Bxb8 {the
beginning of the down trend.} ({Instead} 22. Re3 {would have been preferable}
Rce8 (22... Bxg3 {runs straight into} 23. fxg3 $18 {and the black king os too
exposed.}) 23. Rfe1 Bxg3 24. Qxg3 Rhg8 25. Qf3 Rh8 26. Bxg6+ Kxg6 27. Ne2 e5
28. Qxd5 $18 {It is obviously not a forced line but a sample of how could have
White kept the pressure and the massive initiative.}) 22... Rxb8 23. Qe3 Rbg8
24. Nf3 {exchanging queens solved all Black's problems.} ({As much as I like} 
24. f4 {suggested by computers, that is not an easy human decision to make.}
Nxh4 25. Rf2 $44) 24... Qxe3 25. fxe3 Ke7 {the remainder of the game presents
no more interest for the purpose of this particular excerpt. Black turned the
tables and won the resulting endgame.} 0-1

